  title="The Making of Stars"
  subtitle="A Stars Study — The Vocabulary of a Cult"
  description="You can learn what a culture actually worships by listening to how it talks when it is not being careful. When this culture talks about famous people, it reaches for the vocabulary of religion."
>
  <p class="lede">You can learn what a culture actually worships by listening to how it talks when it is not being careful. Not the creeds it recites — the words it reaches for without thinking. And when this culture talks about famous people, it does not reach for the vocabulary of admiration. It reaches, every single time, for the vocabulary of religion.</p>
  <p>Not one word of what follows is a stretch or a pun. Every term is doing exactly the job it was built to do.</p>

  <h2>I. Count the Words</h2>
  <p>Set them in a row and look at them cold.</p>
  <p>We call these people stars. We call them idols. We call them icons. We say we adore them. We call ourselves their fans. We call them celebrities.</p>
  <p>Six words. Every one of them, without exception, comes out of worship. Not one was borrowed from theater, or from commerce, or from sport. The culture did not run out of ordinary words for a person who is good at a job. It reached past all of them and picked up the liturgy.</p>

  <h2>II. Idol and Icon</h2>
  <p>Start with the two that are not even disguised.</p>
  <p>An idol is a graven image — a made thing, set up to receive what belongs to Yahuah. That is not an old meaning the word has outgrown. It is the meaning. The Word spends whole chapters on it and never once softens.</p>
  <blockquote>
    <p>“Thou shalt not make unto thee any graven image, or any likeness of any thing that is in heaven above, or that is in the earth beneath, or that is in the water under the earth: thou shalt not bow down thyself to them, nor serve them.”</p>
    <cite>Exodus 20:4–5</cite>
  </blockquote>
  <p>An <em>icon</em> is the Greek <strong>eikon</strong> — an image, a likeness. Be honest about this one, because honesty is stronger than exaggeration here: the word itself is clean. Scripture uses it of man made in the likeness of Elohim, and of the Son as the express image. There is nothing pagan in the bare word.</p>
  <p>What happened to it is the point. The institutional church took a clean word for image and turned it into an object — a painted board, kissed, bowed to, carried in procession, credited with power. It manufactured the very thing Exodus 20 forbids and gave it a respectable Greek name. By the time the culture picked the word up for its famous people, the work had already been done. Icon had already come to mean an image men venerate.</p>
  <p>So when a magazine calls a woman an icon, it is not being poetic. It is using the term correctly. She has become an image, and the image receives what people no longer bring to Yahuah.</p>

  <h2>III. Adore and Fan</h2>
  <p>The next two are worse, because they describe not the object but the crowd.</p>
  <p>To <em>adore</em> is, at its root, to worship. The Latin <strong>adorare</strong> means to speak to, to pray to, to address a god. It has never meant simply to like something very much. When a man says he adores her, he is reporting an act of devotion in the plain sense of the word, and he does not know it.</p>
  <p>A <em>fan</em> is a shortening of <em>fanatic</em>, from the Latin <strong>fanaticus</strong> — which comes from <strong>fanum</strong>, a temple. A <em>fanaticus</em> was a man belonging to the temple: inspired by the god, possessed by him, raving in his service. That is not a distant cousin of the modern word. That is the word, with the temple filed off.</p>
  <p>Take those two together and read what the culture is confessing. The crowd worships. The crowd is temple-possessed. It says so out loud, in ordinary English, on the way to the arena.</p>

  <h2>IV. Celebrity: A Crowd With a Name</h2>
  <p>The sixth word is the quietest and it may be the most revealing.</p>
  <p><em>Celebrity</em> comes from the Latin <strong>celebritas</strong> — a multitude, a thronging, a crowded assembly. Its parent <em>celeber</em> meant frequented, thronged, much-attended. The same root gives us <strong>celebrate</strong>.</p>
  <p>So a celebrity is not, at root, a person. A celebrity is a crowd. The word names the throng, not the man in the middle of it — and the crowd is the whole substance of the thing. Remove the multitude and there is no celebrity left, only a person.</p>
  <p>Which tells you where the power in this arrangement actually sits. It is not in him. It is in you.</p>

  <h2>V. Names Pressed Into the Ground</h2>
  <p>Now leave the dictionary and look at what has been built.</p>
  <p>Down the most famous sidewalk in the world, human names are set inside golden stars and pressed into the earth. People travel across oceans to stand over them. They kneel to photograph them. They lay flowers on them when the person dies, and they leave candles burning there through the night.</p>
  <p>Read that description back without the word Hollywood attached to it. Golden figures bearing names, set in the ground, visited by pilgrims who kneel, bring offerings, and light candles. There is no honest way to call that anything but a shrine. It is a shrine with a gift shop, and the pilgrims would be genuinely offended if you told them what they were doing.</p>

  <h2>VI. The Star of Your God</h2>
  <p>And the Word named this exact sin long before there was a camera or a sidewalk. Stephen, in the middle of the sermon that got him killed, reached back and reminded Israel what they had actually carried through the wilderness.</p>
  <blockquote>
    <p>“Yea, ye took up the tabernacle of Moloch, and the star of your god Remphan, figures which ye made to worship them: and I will carry you away beyond Babylon.”</p>
    <cite>Acts 7:43</cite>
  </blockquote>
  <p>Take the phrase apart slowly, because every piece of it is standing on that sidewalk.</p>
  <p>The star of your god. A star, bearing the name of a god, carried and honored.</p>
  <p>Figures which ye made. Not figures that descended. Figures they manufactured — the work of their own hands, then set up to receive worship from the hands that made them.</p>
  <p>That is precisely the mechanic. No one is born a star. A star is manufactured: the name is chosen, the face is built, the story is written, the image is placed in front of a generation until it is loved. Men make the figure, and then men worship the figure they made.</p>
  <blockquote>
    <p>“Their idols are silver and gold, the work of men’s hands. They have mouths, but they speak not: eyes have they, but they see not... They that make them are like unto them; so is every one that trusteth in them.”</p>
    <cite>Psalm 115:4–5, 8</cite>
  </blockquote>
  <p>They that make them are like unto them. That is the sentence the whole industry should be afraid of. You do not walk away from an idol unchanged. You are conformed to what you adore — and a generation that has adored manufactured people is becoming manufactured itself, which is exactly what it looks like.</p>

  <h2>VII. Without a Blush</h2>
  <p>And then there is the piece that requires no interpretation at all.</p>
  <p>One of the most-watched programs of its era was called, on the air, in the listings, in the mouths of millions of families every week: American Idol.</p>
  <p>Nobody hid it. Nobody objected. It was not a coded reference or a hidden confession, and it was not even edgy — it was wholesome family programming. The nation named its idol factory after the sin, out loud, in prime time, and the sin was so completely invisible to the people watching that the name registered as clever rather than as an admission.</p>
  <p>That is the most damning fact in this study. Not that the enemy hid it. That he did not have to.</p>

  <h2>VIII. Keep Yourselves</h2>
  <p>So what does a believer do? Not panic, and not pretend he is above it — the vocabulary is in your mouth too.</p>
  <p>Start where the Word starts: get the words back. Refuse to call a man an idol. Refuse to say you adore anyone but Yahuah. Refuse to be a fanaticus of anything with a temple. The language is not decoration; it is the rail the thinking runs on, and the culture handed you a liturgy and told you it was slang.</p>
  <p>Then measure the trade honestly. Everything a star is given — the attention, the trust, the devotion, the shaping of what you believe and how you speak and what you want — came out of a finite supply. It did not appear from nowhere. It was taken from somewhere.</p>
  <blockquote>
    <p>“I am Yahuah: that is my name: and my glory will I not give to another, neither my praise to graven images.”</p>
    <cite>Isaiah 42:8</cite>
  </blockquote>
  <p>He will not give it to another. But we do, constantly, and we do it with words we never bothered to look up.</p>
  <blockquote>
    <p>“Little children, keep yourselves from idols.”</p>
    <cite>1 John 5:21</cite>
  </blockquote>
  <p>That is the last line of the letter. Not a footnote — the closing charge. John spends the whole book on love and light and truth, and then ends with this, as if he knew what men would do the moment he set down the pen.</p>

